  "prompt": "What does white smoke from motorcycle exhaust mean?",
  "response": "White smoke from a motorcycle exhaust can be indicative of several potential issues:\n\n1. **Condensation**: If the white smoke appears primarily during cold weather or when the engine is first started, it might just be condensation burning off. This is often harmless and should stop once the engine warms up.\n\n2. **Coolant Leak**: White smoke can be a sign of coolant leaking into the engine. This can happen due to a blown head gasket, a cracked engine block, or a damaged cylinder head. Coolant burning in the combustion chamber produces a white, sweet-smelling smoke.\n\n3. **Oil Burning**: White or bluish smoke can also indicate that oil is burning in the engine. This can be due to worn piston rings, valve seals, or other internal engine components. The smoke might look white at first but may turn bluish once the engine heats up.\n\n4. **Fuel Issues**: Problems with the fuel system, such as incorrect fuel mixture (too rich) or impurities in fuel, can also result in white or light-colored smoke.\n\n5. **Excessive Crankcase Oil**: Overfilling the oil can cause it to be drawn into the combustion process, resulting in white smoke.\n\n6. **Aftermarket Additives**: Some fuel or oil additives can produce white smoke as they burn.\n\nWhile some causes of white smoke are benign, others might require immediate attention to avoid further engine damage. It's recommended to consult with a motorcycle mechanic for an accurate diagnosis and proper intervention.",
